TY  - JOUR
T1  - Learning in Repeated Interactions on Networks
AU  - Huang, Wanying
AU  - Strack, Philipp
AU  - Tamuz, Omer
Y1  - 2024/01/01
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2024/01/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA20806
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
JA  - Econometrica
SP  - 1
EP  - 27
VL  - 92
IS  - 1
KW  - Social learning
KW  - social networks
KW  - large deviations
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA20806
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We study how long-lived, rational agents learn in a social network. In every period, after observing the past actions of his neighbors, each agent receives a private signal, and chooses an action whose payoff depends only on the state. Since equilibrium actions depend on higher-order beliefs, it is difficult to characterize behavior. Nevertheless, we show that regardless of the size and shape of the network, the utility function, and the patience of the agents, the speed of learning in any equilibrium is bounded from above by a constant that only depends on the private signal distribution.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Drilling Deadlines and Oil and Gas Development
AU  - Herrnstadt, Evan
AU  - Kellogg, Ryan
AU  - Lewis, Eric
Y1  - 2024/01/01
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2024/01/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA18436
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
JA  - Econometrica
SP  - 29
EP  - 60
VL  - 92
IS  - 1
KW  - Deadlines
KW  - leasing
KW  - royalties
KW  - oil and gas
KW  - drilling
KW  - bunching
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA18436
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Oil and gas leases between mineral owners and extraction firms typically specify a date by which the firm must either drill a well or lose the lease. These deadlines are known as primary terms. Using data from the Louisiana shale boom, we first show that well drilling is substantially bunched just before the primary term deadline. This bunching is not necessarily surplus-reducing: using an estimated model of firms' drilling and input choices, we show that primary terms can increase total surplus by countering the effects of leases' royalties, as royalties are a tax on revenue and delay drilling. These benefits are reduced, however, when production outcomes are sensitive to drilling inputs and when drilling one well indefinitely extends the period of time during which additional wells may be drilled. We enrich the model to consider mineral owners' lease offers and find small effects of primary terms on owners' revenue.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Can Restorative Justice Conferencing Reduce Recidivism? Evidence From the Make-it-Right Program
AU  - Shem-Tov, Yotam
AU  - Raphael, Steven
AU  - Skog, Alissa
Y1  - 2024/01/01
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2024/01/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA20996
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
JA  - Econometrica
SP  - 61
EP  - 78
VL  - 92
IS  - 1
KW  - Restorative justice
KW  - recidivism
KW  - diversion
KW  - juvenile justice
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA20996
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This paper studies the effect of a restorative justice intervention targeted at 143 youth ages 13 to 17 facing felony charges of medium severity (e.g., burglary, assault). Eligible youths were randomly assigned to participate in the Make-it-Right (MIR) restorative justice program or a control group where they faced standard criminal prosecution. We estimate the effects of MIR on the likelihood that a youth will be rearrested in the four years following randomization. Assignment to MIR reduces the probability of a rearrest within six months by 19 percentage points, a 44 percent reduction relative to the control group. Moreover, the reduction in recidivism persists even four years after randomization. Thus, our estimates show that restorative justice conferencing can reduce recidivism among youth charged with relatively serious offenses and can be an effective alternative to traditional criminal justice practices.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Designing Disability Insurance Reforms: Tightening Eligibility Rules or Reducing Benefits?
AU  - Haller, Andreas
AU  - Staubli, Stefan
AU  - Zweimüller, Josef
Y1  - 2024/01/01
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2024/01/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA19021
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
JA  - Econometrica
SP  - 79
EP  - 110
VL  - 92
IS  - 1
KW  - Disability insurance
KW  - screening
KW  - benefits
KW  - policy reform
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA19021
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This paper develops a sufficient statistics framework for analyzing the welfare effects of disability insurance (DI). We derive social-optimality conditions for the two main DI policy parameters: (i) eligibility rules and (ii) benefit levels. Applying this framework to two restrictive DI reforms in Austria, we find that tighter DI eligibility rules triggered higher fiscal cost savings and lower insurance losses. Hence, tighter DI eligibility rules dominate DI benefit reductions in scaling back the Austrian DI system.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Do not Blame Bellman: It Is Koopmans' Fault
AU  - Bloise, Gaetano
AU  - Le Van, Cuong
AU  - Vailakis, Yiannis
Y1  - 2024/01/01
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2024/01/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA20386
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
JA  - Econometrica
SP  - 111
EP  - 140
VL  - 92
IS  - 1
KW  - Stochastic recursive utility
KW  - Koopmans operator
KW  - Bellman operator
KW  - dynamic programming
KW  - multiplicity
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA20386
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We provide a unified approach to stochastic dynamic programming with recursive utility based on an elementary application of Tarski's fixed point theorem. We establish that the exclusive source of multiple values is the presence of multiple recursive utilities consistent with the given aggregator, each yielding a legitimate value of the recursive program. We also present sufficient conditions ensuring a unique value of the recursive program in some circumstances. Overall, acknowledging the unavoidable failure of uniqueness in general, we argue that the greatest fixed point of the Bellman operator should have a privileged position.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - “Near” Weighted Utilitarian Characterizations of Pareto Optima
AU  - Che, Yeon-Koo
AU  - Kim, Jinwoo
AU  - Kojima, Fuhito
AU  - Ryan, Christopher Thomas
Y1  - 2024/01/01
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2024/01/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA18930
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
JA  - Econometrica
SP  - 141
EP  - 165
VL  - 92
IS  - 1
KW  - Pareto optima
KW  - weighted utilitarian welfare maximization
KW  - sequential utilitarian welfare maximization
KW  - hyperreal weights
KW  - weak continuity
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA18930
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We give two characterizations of Pareto optimality via ?near? weighted utilitarian welfare maximization. One characterization sequentially maximizes utilitarian welfare functions using a finite sequence of nonnegative and eventually positive welfare weights. The other maximizes a utilitarian welfare function with a certain class of positive hyperreal weights. The social welfare ordering represented by these ?near? weighted utilitarian welfare criteria is characterized by the standard axioms for weighted utilitarianism under a suitable weakening of the continuity axiom.
ER  - 

